Lines 1329 to 1351 in [50997e3](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/commit/50997e3c3b1f9331d3b03e3867c4896422278e52)

 case NPY_DOUBLE: { 
     double value = *(double *)valueptr; 
     if ((value > -65000 && value < 65000) || !npy_isfinite(value)) { 
         return NPY_HALF; 
     } 
     else if (value > -3.4e38 && value < 3.4e38) { 
         return NPY_FLOAT; 
     } 
     break; 
 } 
 case NPY_LONGDOUBLE: { 
     npy_longdouble value = *(npy_longdouble *)valueptr; 
     if ((value > -65000 && value < 65000) || !npy_isfinite(value)) { 
         return NPY_HALF; 
     } 
     else if (value > -3.4e38 && value < 3.4e38) { 
         return NPY_FLOAT; 
     } 
     else if (value > -1.7e308 && value < 1.7e308) { 
         return NPY_DOUBLE; 
     } 
     break; 
 } 
```
I think that this hardcoded approximation logic isn't correct in either case, since comparison done in double or longdouble space, values right at or near the float32 boundary can be misclassified depending on how the literal is rounded.
So I have a new proposal with the logic,
rather than trying to tune these numeric thresholds, I think a different approach based on representability instead of raw value ranges:

- For a given float scalar (float16/32/64/longdouble), we try candidate smaller float types in order.
- For each candidate type, we cast to that type and back, and check whether the original value can be recovered within that type’s precision.
- Only if the value round-trips (within an epsilon-based tolerance for float64/longdouble) do we demote to that smaller dtype.

I think changing the logic in above way would be better and give more accurate answer.

If I were to be assigned on this issue, I can implement it in the above way
